Short answer: there isn’t one “right” number—there’s a right range.
And for what you’re building, the sweet spot is:

8–12 core keys

⸻

Why 8–12 works (not arbitrary)

1) Human cognition constraint (your “pseudo-c”)
	•	People can actively work with ~7±2 chunks
	•	Beyond that → overload
	•	Below that → not expressive enough

👉 8–12 = maximum power without collapse

⸻

2) Music already solved this problem
	•	Western music → 12 tones
	•	Most melodies → 5–8 notes
	•	Experts use full range, beginners use subset

👉 Same structure you want:
	•	full system = 12
	•	usable subset = ~7–8

⸻

3) Expressiveness vs control tradeoff

Keys	Effect
3–5	Too simple → toy
6–8	Playable → intuition forms
8–12	🔥 sweet spot (depth + usability)
13–20	Specialist only
20+	Library, not instrument


⸻

4) Systems principle (important)

Emergence doesn’t come from more primitives—
it comes from better interactions between a few.

You don’t want:
	•	30 weak patterns

You want:
	•	8–12 orthogonal, composable, reusable ones

⸻

5) Architecture recommendation (clean)

Layered approach:

Core Layer (the instrument)
→ 8–12 keys

Extended Layer (advanced)
→ modifiers / combinations
→ don’t add new keys, add transformations

⸻

6) What those keys should feel like

Each key should be:
	•	distinct (not overlapping)
	•	reusable across domains
	•	intuitively recognizable
	•	composable with others

If two keys feel similar → merge them
If one never gets used → cut it

⸻

7) Clean rule (use this going forward)

“Minimum set that can generate maximum variety.”

⸻

8) Final answer (locked)
	•	Start with: 8 keys
	•	Expand to: 10–12 max
	•	Never exceed: 12 in the core set

⸻

🔥 Why this matters

If you get the number wrong:
	•	too many → no one learns it
	•	too few → no one respects it

If you get it right:

it becomes playable, not theoretical

⸻

Final compression

“A good system isn’t big.
It’s complete.”

